    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the static port gets blocked, it's like a goblin trying to sneak up on the aircraft's airspeed indicator – the airspeed reading will be affected, but not in the same way as a blocked pitot tube.\n\nA blocked static port will cause the airspeed indicator to read a higher airspeed than the actual speed of the aircraft. This is because the static port is providing a reference point for the airspeed indicator, and if it's blocked, the airspeed indicator will think the aircraft is moving faster than it actually is.\n\nOn the other hand, the altitude reading will be unaffected by a blocked static port. The static port is used to measure the static pressure, which is related to the aircraft's altitude, but not directly related to airspeed. So, even if the static port is blocked, the airspeed indicator will still be able to read the correct airspeed, but the altitude reading will remain accurate.\n\nIt's worth noting that a blocked static port can also cause the airspeed indicator to oscillate or fluctuate, which can be confusing for the pilot. This is because the airspeed indicator is trying to compensate for the blocked static port, but it's not getting the correct reference point.",
